<p><b>Director:</b><br>
Lee Pederson, Department of English, Emory University, Atlanta, Georgia
30322.</p>

<p><b>Goals of LARMS and LAWS:</b><br>
LAMR goals include: an inventory of phonemes and a register of regional
and social markers. This research will be helpful in determining what
might be appropriate in the conduct of LAWS research.</p>

<p><b>Areas covered in the LAWS grid:</b><br>
Sixty-five units for research in the Middle Rockies: Wyoming (fifteen),
Colorado (twenty-eight) and Utah (twenty-two). The composition of the
LARMS is a work in progress. It began in 1988 with the organization of
the Wyoming grid. The map identifies Wyoming counties in addition to
providing a model for establishing grid divisions, first for Colorado
and Utah and then for Montana, Idaho, West Texas, New Mexico, Arizona,
California, Oregon, and Washington.</p>

<p><b>Nature of recordings:</b><br>
The Wyoming grid compositions illustrate the method of selection and
arrangement that were used in Colorado, where David Newton and Madsen
completed fieldwork in 1991, and Utah.</p>

<p><b>LARMS protocols:</b><br>
As with the LAGS project the protocol is the central research tool.
Still, unlike LAGS protocols the LARMS texts are complete records of
the interview, organized as prompts and responses, ordered as numbered
exchanges, and cued to worksheet references, with all worksheet items
entered in ABC notation.</p>

